  <title>
   <narrative xml:lang="EN">Gaziantep CNG Buses Project II</narrative>
  </title>
  <description type="1">
   <narrative xml:lang="EN">Turkey is experiencing significant population growth caused by the refugee  influx since the start of the civil war in Syria. Based on recent estimates,  some 2.7 million refugees live in Turkey, placing a huge toll on host  communities which are struggling to provide needed services. This is  particularly the case in areas close to the Syrian border such as Gaziantep,  which is frequently the first point of settlement.  The refugee influx has strained key municipal services in the areas of water,  waste water, urban transport and solid waste operations in Gaziantep. Although  the Turkish government has established refugee camps, the majority of the  refugees live in Gaziantep city centre. 50 per cent of the refugees are women  and youth under 18. Gaziantep Metropolitan Municipality and its entities do not  have the capacity to meet the growing demand for services and face increasingly  strained budgets.  In response, the Bank is developing a refugee response plan which focuses on  building the host country economic resilience. It identifies municipal and  environmental infrastructure as a priority.  The EBRD signed a EUR 10 million loan agreement with Gaziantep Metropolitan  Municipality on 17 November 2011 to finance the acquisition of 50 low floor  buses, essential maintenance equipment and a compressed natual gas  (CNG) filling station. The Bank is now providing a EUR 5 million extension to  the existing loan to finance an additional 50 CNG-powered buses to be used in  public transport in Gaziantep.</narrative>
  </description>
